SIMPLE: haughty
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Haughty
<hw>Haugh"ty</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧"t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Haughtier</adjf>
<pr>(h⟦add⟧"t⟦icr⟧*⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Haughtiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hautein</ets>, F.
<ets>hautain</ets>, fr. <ets>haut</ets> high, OF. also <ets>halt</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>altus</ets>. See <er>Altitude</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>High; lofty; bold.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To measure the most <qex>haughty</qex> mountain's height.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Equal unto this <qex>haughty</qex> enterprise.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disdainfully or contemptuously proud; arrogant;
overbearing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A woman of a <qex>haughty</qex> and imperious nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Indicating haughtiness; <as>as, a <ex>haughty</ex>
carriage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Satan, with vast and <qex>haughty</qex> strides advanced,⟦br⟧
Came towering.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haul</ent>⟦br⟧
